  "prompt": "Does money laundering fall under criminal legislation?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a criminal offense and falls under criminal legislation in most jurisdictions around the world. It involves the process of disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through a complex sequence of banking transfers or commercial transactions. This makes the money appear to come from a legitimate source.\n\nThe specific laws and penalties for money laundering vary by country, but it is widely recognized as a serious crime. International bodies, such as the **Financial Action Task Force (FATF)**, work to combat money laundering and terrorist financing by setting global standards and promoting effective legal, regulatory, and operational measures.\n\nIn many legal systems, money laundering is punishable by significant fines, imprisonment, or both. Additionally, individuals and organizations involved in money laundering may face asset forfeiture, reputational damage, and other consequences. Financial institutions and businesses are often required to implement anti-money laundering (AML) measures to prevent and detect such activities.",
